  "format": "tiptap/v1",
  "doc": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Why GQA Exists"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Multi-Query Attention (MQA) reduces the KV cache to a single set of keys and values shared across all H query heads, shrinking cache memory by H×. But the quality loss on long-context tasks was enough to disqualify MQA for some applications. Grouped-Query Attention (GQA), introduced by Ainslie et al. (2023), places "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "G groups"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " of KV pairs between the two extremes: each group of "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "H/G"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " query heads shares one KV pair. Setting G = H recovers MHA; G = 1 gives MQA."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "GQA diagram showing MHA with 8 individual KV pairs, GQA with 2 shared KV groups of 4 heads each, and MQA with 1 shared KV pair, plus comparison table"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Mechanics"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Given H query heads split into G groups, group g covers heads "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "{g·(H/G), …, (g+1)·(H/G)−1}"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ". Each group has its own projection matrices "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "W_K^g, W_V^g ∈ ℝ^{d_model × d_k}"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ". All H query heads keep their individual projections:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockMath",
        "attrs": {
          "latex": "\\text{head}_h = \\text{Attn}\\!\\left(XW_Q^h,\\; XW_K^{g(h)},\\; XW_V^{g(h)}\\right)"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "where "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "g(h) = ⌊h · G / H⌋"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " maps each query head to its group. The KV cache now holds "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "2 × L × G × T × d_k"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " values — a factor of "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "H/G"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " reduction compared to MHA."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import torch\nimport torch.nn as nn\nimport torch.nn.functional as F\nimport math\n\nclass GroupedQueryAttention(nn.Module):\n    def __init__(self, d_model: int, n_heads: int, n_kv_heads: int):\n        super().__init__()\n        assert n_heads % n_kv_heads == 0\n        self.n_heads    = n_heads\n        self.n_kv_heads = n_kv_heads\n        self.group_size = n_heads // n_kv_heads   # query heads per KV group\n        self.d_k        = d_model // n_heads\n\n        # One Q projection per query head\n        self.W_q = nn.Linear(d_model, n_heads    * self.d_k, bias=False)\n        # One K/V projection per KV group\n        self.W_k = nn.Linear(d_model, n_kv_heads * self.d_k, bias=False)\n        self.W_v = nn.Linear(d_model, n_kv_heads * self.d_k, bias=False)\n        self.W_o = nn.Linear(d_model, d_model,               bias=False)\n\n    def forward(self, x, mask=None):\n        B, T, _ = x.shape\n        H, G, d_k = self.n_heads, self.n_kv_heads, self.d_k\n\n        q = self.W_q(x).view(B, T, H, d_k).transpose(1, 2)  # (B, H, T, d_k)\n        k = self.W_k(x).view(B, T, G, d_k).transpose(1, 2)  # (B, G, T, d_k)\n        v = self.W_v(x).view(B, T, G, d_k).transpose(1, 2)\n\n        # Expand each KV group to cover its query heads\n        # repeat_interleave: (B, G, T, d_k) → (B, H, T, d_k)\n        k = k.repeat_interleave(self.group_size, dim=1)  # (B, H, T, d_k)\n        v = v.repeat_interleave(self.group_size, dim=1)\n\n        scores = (q @ k.transpose(-2, -1)) / math.sqrt(d_k)  # (B, H, T, T)\n        if mask is not None:\n            scores = scores.masked_fill(~mask, float('-inf'))\n        attn = F.softmax(scores, dim=-1)\n        out  = (attn @ v).transpose(1, 2).reshape(B, T, H * d_k)\n        return self.W_o(out)\n\n# Compare parameter counts and KV cache sizes\nfor label, H, G in [('MHA', 8, 8), ('GQA-4', 8, 4), ('GQA-2', 8, 2), ('MQA', 8, 1)]:\n    d_model, T = 512, 1024\n    d_k = d_model // H\n    kv_params  = 2 * G * d_model * d_k         # K + V projection weights\n    kv_cache   = 2 * G * T * d_k * 2           # bfloat16, one layer\n    print(f'{label:7s}: KV params={kv_params//1024:4d} K,  '\n          f'KV cache/layer={kv_cache//1024:5d} KB  (G={G})')\n\n# MHA    : KV params=  64 K,  KV cache/layer=  256 KB  (G=8)\n# GQA-4  : KV params=  32 K,  KV cache/layer=  128 KB  (G=4)\n# GQA-2  : KV params=  16 K,  KV cache/layer=   64 KB  (G=2)\n# MQA    : KV params=   8 K,  KV cache/layer=   32 KB  (G=1)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Converting MHA Checkpoints to GQA"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The Ainslie et al. paper also showed that an already-trained MHA model can be converted to GQA with minimal quality loss via "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "mean-pooling"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " the KV projection weights within each group, followed by a short fine-tuning phase (5% of the original training budget). This makes GQA practical for converting existing MHA models rather than training from scratch."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import torch\n\ndef mha_to_gqa(W_k_mha: torch.Tensor, n_heads: int, n_kv_heads: int) -> torch.Tensor:\n    \"\"\"\n    Convert MHA key/value weight to GQA by mean-pooling groups.\n    W_k_mha: (H * d_k, d_model)  — stacked per-head projections\n    Returns:  (G * d_k, d_model)\n    \"\"\"\n    H, G = n_heads, n_kv_heads\n    group_size = H // G\n    d_k = W_k_mha.shape[0] // H\n    # Reshape to (G, group_size, d_k, d_model), mean over group_size\n    W = W_k_mha.view(G, group_size, d_k, -1)\n    return W.mean(dim=1).view(G * d_k, -1)  # (G * d_k, d_model)\n\n# Example: H=8 heads → G=2 KV groups\nH, G, d_k, d_model = 8, 2, 64, 512\nW_k_mha = torch.randn(H * d_k, d_model)   # original MHA weights\nW_k_gqa = mha_to_gqa(W_k_mha, H, G)\nprint(f'MHA W_k: {W_k_mha.shape}')        # (512, 512)\nprint(f'GQA W_k: {W_k_gqa.shape}')        # (128, 512)  — 4× fewer rows\n\n# In HuggingFace: load a converted GQA model directly\n# from transformers import AutoModelForCausalLM\n# model = AutoModelForCausalLM.from_pretrained('meta-llama/Llama-2-70b-hf')\n# model.config.num_key_value_heads  # → 8 (GQA with G=8, H=64)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Quality vs Efficiency Results"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The 2023 paper benchmarked T5 XXL (11B) converted from MHA to GQA with G=8 groups. On summarisation (CNN/DailyMail), translation (WMT English–German), and long-context QA (TriviaQA), GQA G=8 matched MHA quality within 0.3 ROUGE-2 / 0.5 BLEU, while MQA (G=1) showed gaps of 0.5–1.5 points. Decoding speedup at batch=1 was 1.6–2.1× for GQA and 2.1–2.8× for MQA, both versus MHA."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "LLaMA 2 70B (released 2023) adopts GQA with H=64 query heads and G=8 KV groups, reducing the per-layer KV cache 8×. LLaMA 3 8B and 70B continue this pattern. Mistral 7B uses G=8 with H=32, giving a 4× cache reduction. GQA is now the default for production LLMs above ~7B parameters."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockquote",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "marks": [
                  {
                    "type": "bold"
                  }
                ],
                "text": "Choosing G in practice: "
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "Start with G = H/8 (i.e., 8 query heads per KV group). If the cache still doesn't fit, try G = H/16. If quality degrades noticeably on your evaluation set, increase G toward H/4. The crossover point where GQA quality equals MHA quality is typically G = 4–8 for models up to 70B. Avoid G = 1 (MQA) unless memory is extremely tight and a small quality drop is acceptable."
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
}
